# Steven Christopher — UI Vibe Rules

Mood anchor: cinematic, nocturnal, minimal, emotionally unresolved. A 2am indie
film scene, not a pop campaign. If a change makes the site feel like an app, a
SaaS landing page, or an influencer site — it is wrong.

## Color

- Primary: black, charcoal, off-white, washed gray
- Accents (sparingly): deep muted red, desaturated navy, faded steel blue
- Low saturation. No neon. No high-contrast brights.
- Texture and lighting matter more than color.

## Typography

- Headings: elegant serif (editorial, restrained)
- Body / nav: neutral sans-serif
- Never mix more than two families. No trendy, distorted, or futuristic faces.
- Type supports the mood; it never dominates.

## Layout & motion

- Negative space is the layout.
- Slow, intentional transitions. No springy, bouncy, or attention-grabbing motion.
- No scroll-jacking. No aggressive parallax.
- Hero areas: full-bleed image or video, sparse text.
- Navigation: `Music`, `Video`, `Contact`. Keep it minimal.

## Device priority — mobile-first, always

- ~99% of traffic is mobile. Design, build, and review every layout at ~375px
  width first. Desktop is the upscale, not the source of truth.
- `:hover` is a progressive enhancement only. Never gate critical information,
  state changes, navigation, or affordances behind hover-only reveals — every
  hover effect must have an equivalent always-visible or tap-driven state that
  works on touch.
- No hover-triggered tooltips, captions, or labels as the sole way to convey
  meaning. If a desktop interaction wouldn't survive on an iPhone, redesign it.

## Forever-new catalog — no release dates on music or video

- Never render release dates, drop dates, "year" labels, "released" pills, or
  any month/year metadata on music releases or music videos. The catalog must
  feel timeless and current; visible gaps between releases break the spell.
- Sorting collections by `releaseDate` internally is fine; rendering the value
  in the UI is not. The same rule applies to videos (`data.date`).
- Allowed date usage: footer copyright year,
  press article publication dates. Music + video items show format/type and
  title only — nothing time-stamped.

## Copy

- Minimal, selective, emotionally restrained.
- One line beats a paragraph. Never desperate, performatively edgy, sentimental,
  or over-explanatory.
- No marketing-speak, no exclamation marks, no emoji.

## Reject these patterns

- Glossy pop aesthetics, influencer styling, heavy retouching
- Bright commercial lighting in imagery
- Dashboard / startup / SaaS visual language
- Dense UI, busy layouts, CTA-stacked sections
- Decorative gradients, drop shadows for "depth", glassmorphism
- Generic stock photography

## When deeper brand context is needed

For narrative tone, photography direction, voice, copywriting, image
generation, campaign concepts, or artist references, read the canonical brief
